gene_name: ArmR a 53-amino-acid antirepressor allosterically inhibits MexR dimer-DNA binding by occupying a hydrophobic binding cavity within the center of the MexR dimer. ArmR up-regulation and MexR-ArmR complex formation have previously been shown to upregulate MexAB-OprM.

HMB-1 gene was chromosomally located as part of a Tn 3 family transposon that was named Tn 6345 where expression of bla HMB-1 in E. coli TOP10 led to increased resistance to beta-lactams.

A macrolide glycosyltransferase encoded by the mgtA gene in Streptomyces lividans. This enzyme inactivates macrolides using UDP-glucose as a cofactor. Its optimal substrates are lankamycin calcomycin rosaramicin methymycin and pikromycin while interactions with erythomycin oldeandomycin azithromycin and tylosin were weaker. A macrolide glycosyltransferase encoded by the gimA gene in Streptomyces ambofaciens a natural producer of the macrolide antibiotic spiramycin. Chalcomycin methymycin tylosin pikromycin rosaramicin oleandomycin josamycin and carbomycin are preferred substrates of gimA glycosyltransferase while erythromycin and spiramycin have notably low binding affinities. GimA may be able to inactivate spiramycin precursors. Described by Gourmelen et al. 1998.

It is inactive against spiramycin and carbomycin. Mechanism first described by Cundliffe 1992.

A macrolide glycosyltransferase encoded by the gimA gene in Streptomyces ambofaciens a natural producer of the macrolide antibiotic spiramycin. Chalcomycin methymycin tylosin pikromycin rosaramicin oleandomycin josamycin and carbomycin are preferred substrates of gimA glycosyltransferase while erythromycin and spiramycin have notably low binding affinities. A macrolide glycosyltransferase encoded by the mgtA gene in Streptomyces lividans. This enzyme inactivates macrolides using UDP-glucose as a cofactor. Its optimal substrates are lankamycin calcomycin rosaramicin methymycin and pikromycin while interactions with erythomycin oldeandomycin azithromycin and tylosin were weaker. It is inactive against spiramycin and carbomycin. Mechanism first described by Cundliffe 1992.

A macrolide glycosyltransferase encoded by the gimA gene in Streptomyces ambofaciens a natural producer of the macrolide antibiotic spiramycin. Chalcomycin methymycin tylosin pikromycin rosaramicin oleandomycin josamycin and carbomycin are preferred substrates of gimA glycosyltransferase while erythromycin and spiramycin have notably low binding affinities. GimA may be able to inactivate spiramycin precursors. Described by Gourmelen et al. 1998.

A macrolide glycosyltransferase encoded by the mgtA gene in Streptomyces lividans. This enzyme inactivates macrolides using UDP-glucose as a cofactor. Its optimal substrates are lankamycin calcomycin rosaramicin methymycin and pikromycin while interactions with erythomycin oldeandomycin azithromycin and tylosin were weaker. It is inactive against spiramycin and carbomycin. Mechanism first described by Cundliffe 1992.

An enzyme that confers resistance to fosfomycin in Serratia marcescens by breaking the epoxide ring of the molecule. MsbA is a multidrug resistance transporter homolog from E. coli and belongs to a superfamily of transporters that contain an adenosine triphosphate (ATP) binding cassette (ABC) which is also called a nucleotide-binding domain (NBD). MsbA is a member of the MDR-ABC transporter group by sequence homology. MsbA transports lipid A a major component of the bacterial outer cell membrane and is the only bacterial ABC transporter that is essential for cell viability.

YojI mediates resistance to the peptide antibiotic microcin J25 when it is expressed from a multicopy vector. YojI is capable of pumping out microcin molecules.  The outer membrane protein TolC in addition to YojI is required for export of microcin J25 out of the cell. Microcin J25 is thus the first known substrate for YojI.

MsbA is a multidrug resistance transporter homolog from E. coli and belongs to a superfamily of transporters that contain an adenosine triphosphate (ATP) binding cassette (ABC) which is also called a nucleotide-binding domain (NBD). MsbA is a member of the MDR-ABC transporter group by sequence homology. MsbA transports lipid A a major component of the bacterial outer cell membrane and is the only bacterial ABC transporter that is essential for cell viability.

YojI mediates resistance to the peptide antibiotic microcin J25 when it is expressed from a multicopy vector. YojI is capable of pumping out microcin molecules.  The outer membrane protein TolC in addition to YojI is required for export of microcin J25 out of the cell. Microcin J25 is thus the first known substrate for YojI.

Due to gene duplication the genomes of Nocardia species include both rifampin-sensitive beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB) and rifampin-resistant beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB2) genes with ~88% similarity between the two gene products. Expression of the rpoB2 variant results in replacement of rifampin sensitivity with rifampin resistance.

MdtB is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex with MdtC to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex.

MdtC is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex with MdtB to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex. In the absence of MdtB MdtC can form a homomultimer complex that results in a functioning efflux complex with a narrower drug specificity. mdtC corresponds to 3 loci in Pseudomonas aeruginosa PAO1 (gene name: muxC/muxB) and 3 loci in Pseudomonas aeruginosa LESB58.

Due to gene duplication the genomes of Nocardia species include both rifampin-sensitive beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB) and rifampin-resistant beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB2) genes with ~88% similarity between the two gene products. Bifidobacterium are antibiotic resistant probiotics are prescribed to upkeep the population beneficial bacteria in the gut microbiome. However horizontal gene transfer among gut microbes could create harmful antibiotic-resistant pathogenic bacteria such as Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Lokesh et al. analyzed Bifidobacterium antitubercular drug resistance and mutations in rpoB. They found that B. animalis B. longum and B. adolescentis showed considerable resistance to pyrazinamide isoniazid and streptomycin while B. adolescentis had mutations both in the rifampicin (RIF) pocket and in regions outside the pockets and also showed considerable resistance to RIF.
MuxC is one of the two necessary RND components of the MuxABC-OpmB efflux pumps system in Pseudomonas aeruginosa.
OpmB is an outer membrane efflux protein in Pseudomonas aeruginosa that shows functional cooperation with MuxABC to form the efflux pump system MuxABC-OpmB.

EvgS is a sensor protein that phosphorylates the regulatory protein EvgA. evgS corresponds to 1 locus in Pseudomonas aeruginosa PAO1 and 1 locus in Pseudomonas aeruginosa LESB58.

Bifidobacterium are antibiotic resistant probiotics are prescribed to upkeep the population beneficial bacteria in the gut microbiome. However horizontal gene transfer among gut microbes could create harmful antibiotic-resistant pathogenic bacteria such as Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Lokesh et al. analyzed Bifidobacterium antitubercular drug resistance and mutations in rpoB. They found that B. animalis B. longum and B. adolescentis showed considerable resistance to pyrazinamide isoniazid and streptomycin while B. adolescentis had mutations both in the rifampicin (RIF) pocket and in regions outside the pockets and also showed considerable resistance to RIF.

MdtB is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex with MdtC to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex.

MdtC is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex with MdtB to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex. In the absence of MdtB MdtC can form a homomultimer complex that results in a functioning efflux complex with a narrower drug specificity. mdtC corresponds to 3 loci in Pseudomonas aeruginosa PAO1 (gene name: muxC/muxB) and 3 loci in Pseudomonas aeruginosa LESB58.

AmvA has 14 alpha-helical transmembrane segments qualifying it as a member of the DHA2 transporter family of the major facilitator superfamily (MFS). AmvA from the AC0037 strain of A. baumannii was tested.

Due to gene duplication the genomes of Nocardia species include both rifampin-sensitive beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB) and rifampin-resistant beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB2) genes with ~88% similarity between the two gene products. PmpM is a multidrug efflux pump belonging to the MATE family of Pseudomonas aeruginosa. PmpM is an H+ drug antiporter and is the first reported case of an H+ coupled efflux pump in the MATE family. PmpM confers resistance to fluoroquinolones fradiomycin benzalkonium chloride chlorhexidine gluconate ethidium bromide tetraphenylphosphonium chloride (TPPCl) and rhodamine 6G.

MFS transporters are secondary active transporters with single-polypeptide chains containing 400-600 amino acids that transport small solutes across the membrane by using electrochemical gradients. MsbA is a multidrug resistance transporter homolog from E. coli and belongs to a superfamily of transporters that contain an adenosine triphosphate (ATP) binding cassette (ABC) which is also called a nucleotide-binding domain (NBD). MsbA is a member of the MDR-ABC transporter group by sequence homology. MsbA transports lipid A a major component of the bacterial outer cell membrane and is the only bacterial ABC transporter that is essential for cell viability.

YojI mediates resistance to the peptide antibiotic microcin J25 when it is expressed from a multicopy vector. YojI is capable of pumping out microcin molecules. Bifidobacterium are antibiotic resistant probiotics are prescribed to upkeep the population beneficial bacteria in the gut microbiome. However horizontal gene transfer among gut microbes could create harmful antibiotic-resistant pathogenic bacteria such as Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Lokesh et al. analyzed Bifidobacterium antitubercular drug resistance and mutations in rpoB. They found that B. animalis B. longum and B. adolescentis showed considerable resistance to pyrazinamide isoniazid and streptomycin while B. adolescentis had mutations both in the rifampicin (RIF) pocket and in regions outside the pockets and also showed considerable resistance to RIF.
Bifidobacteria have an intrinsically resistant form of ileS (isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase) that confers resistance to mupirocin.

Lokesh et al. analyzed Bifidobacterium antitubercular drug resistance and mutations in rpoB. They found that B. animalis B. longum and B. adolescentis showed considerable resistance to pyrazinamide isoniazid and streptomycin while B. adolescentis had mutations both in the rifampicin (RIF) pocket and in regions outside the pockets and also showed considerable resistance to RIF.
Bifidobacteria have an intrinsically resistant form of ileS (isoleucyl-tRNA synthetase) that confers resistance to mupirocin.

MdtB is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex with MdtC to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex.

MdtC is a transporter that forms a heteromultimer complex with MdtB to form a multidrug transporter. MdtBC is part of the MdtABC-TolC efflux complex. In the absence of MdtB MdtC can form a homomultimer complex that results in a functioning efflux complex with a narrower drug specificity. mdtC corresponds to 3 loci in Pseudomonas aeruginosa PAO1 (gene name: muxC/muxB) and 3 loci in Pseudomonas aeruginosa LESB58.

Due to gene duplication the genomes of Nocardia species include both rifampin-sensitive beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB) and rifampin-resistant beta-subunit of RNA polymerase (rpoB2) genes with ~88% similarity between the two gene products. Expression of the rpoB2 variant results in replacement of rifampin sensitivity with rifampin resistance.

EvgS is a sensor protein that phosphorylates the regulatory protein EvgA. evgS corresponds to 1 locus in Pseudomonas aeruginosa PAO1 and 1 locus in Pseudomonas aeruginosa LESB58.
